				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
					<p>If you are a dog parent, you=E2=80=99ve heard this before =E2=80=93=
 one year for your two-legged family member is equivalent to seven years fo=
r your four-legged family member. But how true is this? It turns out the ma=
th isn=E2=80=99t that simple.</p>
<p>It is true that dogs age more rapidly than us humans =E2=80=93 but sever=
al factors come into play on how fast they truly mature.</p>
<p>Dogs age more rapidly early on, so the first year of their life is equal=
 to about 15 human years.</p>
<p>Size and breed matters. Smaller dogs tend to live longer than larger dog=
s, but they may mature more quickly in the first few years of life. A large=
-breed canine might age more slowly at first, but be nearing middle age at =
only five years. Tiny dogs and toy breeds don=E2=80=99t become seniors unti=
l around age 10. Medium-sized dogs are somewhere in the middle on both coun=
ts.</p>
<p><em><strong>But don=E2=80=99t worry! No matter how old your dog is, they=
 will always be your puppy.</strong></em></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
